            <h1>
                Why Employers Run Background Checks
            </h1>
            <div>
                The number of background checks conducted in the United States has exploded over
                the past decade. Historically background checks were most commonly used for pre-employment
                screening of job candidates; but they are now increasingly being used for a variety
                of reasons, including verifying prospective tenant screening, medical purposes,
                babysitting, establishing memberships, schools, and creditworthiness. Background
                checks have expanded so much so, that they are now common when making certain transactions
                (e.g. firearm purchases). It is estimated that a person will go through nearly 100
                type of checks in their lifetime. But are these information checks really necessary?
                According to organization that rely on making informed decisions, yes! Studies show
                that with the current tight job market,<span class="boldText"> more than half of job
                    applicants lie</span> on their resumes. As a result attracting qualified employees
                are one of the most significant challenge organizations face. Pre-employment screening
                helps pinpoint those who are untrustworthy, while boosting the employment opportunities
                of those who screen well.
            </div>
